### Custom Gutenberg blocks

Block namespace is `<BLOCK_NAMESPACE>/` (e.g. `radicle/`, `acme/` — pick one per project and stay consistent).

Each block requires four files:

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `app/Blocks/MyBlock.php` | PHP render class; maps `$block['attrs']` to a Blade view via `view('blocks.my-block')->render()` |
| `resources/views/blocks/my-block.blade.php` | Blade template for server-side rendering |
| `resources/js/editor/my-block.block.jsx` | Gutenberg editor component (exports `name`, `title`, `attributes`, `edit`, `save`) |
| `resources/css/app.css` + `editor.css` | Block styles must be added to **both** — `app.css` for frontend, `editor.css` for Gutenberg preview |

To scaffold a new block, use `/sage-wp-toolkit:make-acorn-block` (from raw HTML) or `/sage-wp-toolkit:figma-to-block` (from a Figma URL).
To add a branding-settings section, use `/sage-wp-toolkit:add-branding-section`.

### CSS architecture

`app.css` uses `@import "tailwindcss"` and imports layer files in this order:
`base.css` → `component.css` → `layout.css` → `utilities.css` → `custom.css`

`editor.css` mirrors all block CSS — required for Gutenberg editor preview parity.

**Always reuse existing tokens — never hardcode hex or pixel values.** Full rules enforced by the `sage-wp-toolkit:frontend-code-rules` skill.

### BrandingServiceProvider pattern (if used)

Site-wide config lives in `wp_options` keys prefixed `<OPTION_PREFIX>_*`. See `/sage-wp-toolkit:add-branding-section` for the pattern.

### Vite

`vite.config.js` `base` should match the Bedrock/WordPress public path for this environment. Aliases: `@scripts` → `resources/js`, `@styles` → `resources/css`, `@fonts` → `resources/fonts`, `@images` → `resources/images`.

`@wordpress/blocks` and `@wordpress/dom-ready` are provided by WordPress at runtime — do not bundle them.
